1
00:00:02.135 --> 00:00:05.472
In a basic RAG
pipeline, LLMS are only used for synthesis.

2
00:00:05.972 --> 00:00:09.242
The previous lesson showed you
how to use our LLMs to make a decision

3
00:00:09.242 --> 00:00:11.845
by picking a choice of different
pipelines.

4
00:00:11.845 --> 00:00:16.216
This is, a simplified form of tool calling,
and in this lesson, we'll show you

5
00:00:16.249 --> 00:00:19.352
how to use an LLM
to not only pick a function to execute,

6
00:00:19.652 --> 00:00:22.622
but also infer an argument
to pass through the function.

7
00:00:22.756 --> 00:00:25.759
All right, let's start coding.

8
00:00:25.759 --> 00:00:28.361
One of the promises of our LLMs
is their ability

9
00:00:28.361 --> 00:00:31.498
to take actions and interact
with their external environment.

10
00:00:32.132 --> 00:00:33.299
Unnecessary component

11
00:00:33.299 --> 00:00:36.669
to make this possible is a good interface
for the LLMs to use.

12
00:00:37.103 --> 00:00:40.640
We call this tool
calling and a basic RAG pipeline,

13
00:00:40.673 --> 00:00:43.343
LLMs are only used for synthesis.

14
00:00:43.343 --> 00:00:44.144
The previous lesson

15
00:00:44.144 --> 00:00:47.714
showed you how to use our LLMs
in a slightly more sophisticated manner,

16
00:00:48.114 --> 00:00:51.384
by using it to pick the best
query pipeline to answer the user query.

17
00:00:52.085 --> 00:00:55.088
This is a simplified form of tool calling.

18
00:00:55.188 --> 00:00:58.958
In this lesson, we'll show you how to use
an LLM to not only pick a function

19
00:00:58.958 --> 00:01:02.695
to execute, but also infer an argument
to pass to the function.

20
00:01:03.430 --> 00:01:05.799
This allows the LLM
to figure out how to use

21
00:01:05.799 --> 00:01:08.868
a vector db
instead of just consuming its outputs.

22
00:01:09.335 --> 00:01:12.872
And the final result, is
that users are able to ask more questions

23
00:01:13.073 --> 00:01:13.740
and get back

24
00:01:13.740 --> 00:01:17.577
more precise results than standard
RAG techniques through tool calling.

25
00:01:18.778 --> 00:01:20.380
So let's get started.

26
00:01:20.380 --> 00:01:23.383
Similar to before, we are first going
to set up our OpenAI queu.

27
00:01:23.850 --> 00:01:27.320
We are also going to set up and import
our nest async IO module.

28
00:01:27.587 --> 00:01:31.257
Next, we'll give you a basic overview
and introduction to tool calling.

29
00:01:31.891 --> 00:01:36.096
We'll show you how to find
a tool interface from a Python function.

30
00:01:36.963 --> 00:01:39.899
And the LLM will automatically
infer the parameters

31
00:01:39.899 --> 00:01:43.870
from the signature of the Python function
using LlamaIndex abstractions.

32
00:01:44.771 --> 00:01:47.340
To illustrate this,
let's first define to toy

33
00:01:47.340 --> 00:01:50.343
calculator functions
and show you how tool calling works.

34
00:01:50.610 --> 00:01:53.680
We'll define an add function
and also a mystery function.

35
00:01:55.448 --> 00:01:58.618
The core abstraction in LlamaIndex
is the function tool.

36
00:01:59.719 --> 00:02:03.523
This function tool wraps any given
Python function that you feed it.

37
00:02:03.890 --> 00:02:08.161
And so we see that the function tool takes
in both the add function defined here,

38
00:02:08.561 --> 00:02:12.332
as well as a mystery function
which is just x plus y times x plus y.

39
00:02:13.700 --> 00:02:15.768
You see that both add and mystery

40
00:02:15.768 --> 00:02:20.573
have type annotations for both the x
and y variables, as well as the docstring.

41
00:02:21.741 --> 00:02:24.110
This is not just for stylistic purposes,

42
00:02:24.110 --> 00:02:25.912
this is actually important
because these things

43
00:02:25.912 --> 00:02:28.915
will be used as a prompt for the LLM.

44
00:02:29.883 --> 00:02:32.352
Our function tools
integrate natively with the function

45
00:02:32.352 --> 00:02:35.555
calling capabilities of many LLM models,
including OpenAI.

46
00:02:36.689 --> 00:02:38.625
To pass the tools to an LLM,

47
00:02:38.625 --> 00:02:42.228
you have to import the LLM module
and then call, predict

48
00:02:42.228 --> 00:02:45.231
and call.

49
00:02:45.698 --> 00:02:47.400
This code snippet imports

50
00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:50.403
the OpenAI module explicitly,

51
00:02:50.703 --> 00:02:53.506
and you see that the model is 3.5 turbo.

52
00:02:53.506 --> 00:02:56.743
And then we call the predict
and call function on top of the LLM.

53
00:02:58.011 --> 00:03:01.114
What predict and call does is
it takes in a set of tools

54
00:03:01.648 --> 00:03:05.585
as well as an input prompt string
or a series of chat messages.

55
00:03:06.152 --> 00:03:09.422
And then it's able to both make a decision
of the tool to call,

56
00:03:09.756 --> 00:03:12.992
as well as call the tool itself
and get back the final response.

57
00:03:13.426 --> 00:03:13.860
Here we

58
00:03:13.860 --> 00:03:17.630
see the intermediate steps
calling function mystery with arguments.

59
00:03:17.664 --> 00:03:19.499
You know x equals two, y equals nine.

60
00:03:19.499 --> 00:03:22.602
So we see that at least I call the right
tools and also infer the right parameters.

61
00:03:23.303 --> 00:03:27.140
And the output is 121
and 11 times 11 is 121.

62
00:03:27.173 --> 00:03:28.541
So we got back the right answer.

63
00:03:28.541 --> 00:03:33.313
Note that this simple example effectively
is an expanded version of the router.

64
00:03:34.047 --> 00:03:34.847
Not only does

65
00:03:34.847 --> 00:03:38.484
the LLM pick the tool, but also decides
what parameters to give to the tool.

66
00:03:39.085 --> 00:03:41.754
Let's use this key concept
to define a slightly

67
00:03:41.754 --> 00:03:44.757
more sophisticated
agentic layer on top of vector search.

68
00:03:45.592 --> 00:03:49.596
Not only can the LLM choose vector search,
we can also get it to infer

69
00:03:49.596 --> 00:03:52.665
metadata filters,
which is a structured list of tags

70
00:03:52.966 --> 00:03:56.069
that helps to return a more precise
set of search results.

71
00:03:57.170 --> 00:03:59.239
We'll use the same paper, Meta GPT,

72
00:03:59.239 --> 00:04:02.108
as before,
and this time let's pay attention

73
00:04:02.108 --> 00:04:05.478
to the nodes themselves or the chunks,
because we'll take a look

74
00:04:05.478 --> 00:04:08.481
at the actual metadata
attached to these chunks.

75
00:04:08.581 --> 00:04:12.318
Similar to the last lesson, we'll use
simple directory reader from LlamaIndex

76
00:04:12.485 --> 00:04:13.052
to load

77
00:04:13.052 --> 00:04:16.055
in the parse
representation of this PDF file.

78
00:04:18.524 --> 00:04:19.058
Next,

79
00:04:19.058 --> 00:04:22.495
similar to the last lesson,
we'll use the sentence splitter to split

80
00:04:22.495 --> 00:04:26.399
these documents into a set of even chunks
with a chunk size of 1024.

81
00:04:29.335 --> 00:04:31.638
Each node here represents a chunk,

82
00:04:31.638 --> 00:04:34.841
and let's actually take a look
at the content of an example chunk.

83
00:04:35.842 --> 00:04:38.845
So we'll take a look
at the content of the very first chunk.

84
00:04:39.779 --> 00:04:42.148
And we can do this from doing node dot

85
00:04:42.148 --> 00:04:44.217
Get content.

86
00:04:44.217 --> 00:04:48.721
We set metadata mode equals all,
which is a special setting to actually

87
00:04:48.721 --> 00:04:52.258
not just enable you to print out
the content of the node itself, but

88
00:04:52.258 --> 00:04:55.828
also the metadata attached to the document
which is propagated to every node.

89
00:05:00.066 --> 00:05:02.769
Here we see that once we print this out,

90
00:05:02.769 --> 00:05:07.006
we not only get back a parce representation
of the front page of the paper,

91
00:05:07.974 --> 00:05:10.977
we can also see
the metadata attached at the very top.

92
00:05:11.878 --> 00:05:13.880
So this includes a few things.

93
00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:16.649
This includes page label equal to one.

94
00:05:16.649 --> 00:05:19.919
This includes
file name, metagpt dot PDF file

95
00:05:19.919 --> 00:05:22.922
type, file size and credit and dates.

96
00:05:23.189 --> 00:05:26.793
We'll pay special attention
to the page labels because you know,

97
00:05:26.793 --> 00:05:30.897
for instance, if we actually go in
and try out a different node,

98
00:05:31.230 --> 00:05:34.467
we see that, we actually get back
a different page number.

99
00:05:34.867 --> 00:05:38.037
And so we actually add a page number
annotation to every chunk.

100
00:05:39.539 --> 00:05:42.542
Next we'll define a vector store
index over these notes.

101
00:05:44.177 --> 00:05:45.478
Similar to the last lesson.

102
00:05:45.478 --> 00:05:49.349
This will basically build a RAG
indexing pipeline over these nodes.

103
00:05:49.816 --> 00:05:52.919
It will add an embedding for each node
and it'll get back a query engine.

104
00:05:54.454 --> 00:05:55.588
Differently from last time,

105
00:05:55.588 --> 00:05:59.792
we can actually try querying
this RAG pipeline via metadata filters.

106
00:06:00.126 --> 00:06:02.628
Just to show you how metadata
filtering works.

107
00:06:02.628 --> 00:06:05.631
So we import this object
called metadata filters.

108
00:06:05.798 --> 00:06:09.235
And then we simply specify a filter
where the page label

109
00:06:09.235 --> 00:06:11.137
is equal to the value two.

110
00:06:11.137 --> 00:06:14.006
In addition to top k equals two.

111
00:06:14.006 --> 00:06:16.209
So once we define this as a query engine

112
00:06:16.209 --> 00:06:19.212
and we call
what are some high level results of

113
00:06:20.413 --> 00:06:21.481
Meta GPT, if we take a look

114
00:06:21.481 --> 00:06:24.617
at the source nodes,
once we run this and we call

115
00:06:24.650 --> 00:06:28.421
what are some high level results
a meta gpt and we get back a response.

116
00:06:28.955 --> 00:06:31.958
We'll first
take a look at the response string.

117
00:06:33.292 --> 00:06:36.295
Which outlines the overall results Meta GPT.

118
00:06:36.896 --> 00:06:39.132
But crucially we'll take
a look at the page numbers.

119
00:06:44.570 --> 00:06:47.006
And we see that
as we iterate through the source nodes,

120
00:06:47.006 --> 00:06:50.009
we can actually print out the metadata
attached to these source nodes.

121
00:06:50.510 --> 00:06:53.279
And we see that here
are the page labels equal to two.

122
00:06:53.279 --> 00:06:56.749
And so we see that it's able
to properly filter out the page numbers

123
00:06:57.116 --> 00:06:58.184
to only restrict

124
00:06:58.184 --> 00:07:01.354
the search to the set of pages
where the page label is equal to two.

125
00:07:02.622 --> 00:07:04.757
The last section of this lesson
will allow us

126
00:07:04.757 --> 00:07:07.760
to wrap this overall retrieval tool
into a function.

127
00:07:07.994 --> 00:07:11.998
This function takes in both the query
string and page numbers as filters.

128
00:07:12.732 --> 00:07:17.270
The LLM can actually then infer
the page numbers to filter for a user

129
00:07:17.270 --> 00:07:21.207
query, instead of actually having the user
manually specify the metadata filters.

130
00:07:21.674 --> 00:07:25.144
Just a quick note over here
is that the metadata is not only limited

131
00:07:25.144 --> 00:07:25.945
to page numbers.

132
00:07:25.945 --> 00:07:29.849
As you've seen, you can define
whatever metadata you want like section

133
00:07:29.849 --> 00:07:34.187
IDs, headers, footers, or anything else
through LlamaIndex abstractions.

134
00:07:34.754 --> 00:07:37.223
The ability to use many metadata filters

135
00:07:37.223 --> 00:07:40.026
is especially prominent
and better models like GPT-4.

136
00:07:40.026 --> 00:07:42.028
So we highly encourage you
to check that out.

137
00:07:42.028 --> 00:07:45.198
Here we'll define a Python function
that encapsulates this.

138
00:07:45.398 --> 00:07:49.035
We define a function called vector query,
which takes in the query as well

139
00:07:49.035 --> 00:07:49.802
as page numbers.

140
00:07:50.937 --> 00:07:51.537
This allows

141
00:07:51.537 --> 00:07:54.540
you to perform a vector
search over an index,

142
00:07:54.540 --> 00:07:57.543
along with specifying page numbers
as a metadata filter.

143
00:07:58.077 --> 00:08:00.480
At the very end,
we see that we define a vector query

144
00:08:00.480 --> 00:08:03.483
tool equals
function tool from defaults.

145
00:08:03.749 --> 00:08:07.620
So we pass in the vector
query function into a vector query tool,

146
00:08:07.720 --> 00:08:10.723
which allows us to
then use it with a language model.

147
00:08:12.191 --> 00:08:14.427
So let's try calling this tool
with an LLM,

148
00:08:14.427 --> 00:08:17.129
specifically 3.5 turbo.

149
00:08:17.129 --> 00:08:19.098
We'll find that the LLM is able to infer

150
00:08:19.098 --> 00:08:22.101
both the string
as well as the metadata filters.

151
00:08:22.201 --> 00:08:26.873
We do product and call on the vector
query tool and ask the same question high

152
00:08:26.906 --> 00:08:29.909
level results of Meta GPT
as described on page two.

153
00:08:31.777 --> 00:08:34.780
Here we see that the LLM is able
to formulate the right query

154
00:08:34.847 --> 00:08:39.018
high level results of Meta GPT as well as specify
the page numbers, which is two.

155
00:08:40.219 --> 00:08:43.222
And we get back the correct answer.

156
00:08:44.624 --> 00:08:46.492
Similarly, as before,

157
00:08:46.492 --> 00:08:49.495
we can just quickly
verify the source notes.

158
00:08:51.097 --> 00:08:53.499
And we see that
the page label of the source notes

159
00:08:53.499 --> 00:08:56.602
there is one source note returned
and it has a page label of two.

160
00:08:58.070 --> 00:09:01.507
Finally, we can bring in the summary tool
from the router example

161
00:09:01.507 --> 00:09:02.842
in the first lesson.

162
00:09:02.842 --> 00:09:05.511
And we can combine that
with the vector tool to create this

163
00:09:05.511 --> 00:09:08.514
overall tool picking system.

164
00:09:09.882 --> 00:09:13.352
So this code just sets up a summary index
over the same set of notes

165
00:09:13.586 --> 00:09:16.589
and wraps us in a summary tool
similar to lesson one.

166
00:09:20.226 --> 00:09:22.228
Now let's try a tool calling again.

167
00:09:22.228 --> 00:09:25.798
So the LLM has a slightly harder
task of actually picking the right tool

168
00:09:25.798 --> 00:09:28.034
in addition
to inferring the function parameters.

169
00:09:32.672 --> 00:09:33.940
We asked what our

170
00:09:33.940 --> 00:09:36.742
comparisons with chapter
five on page eight.

171
00:09:36.742 --> 00:09:40.846
We see that it still calls a vector tool,
actually with page number equal to eight,

172
00:09:41.480 --> 00:09:44.483
and it's able
to still give back the right answer.

173
00:09:45.384 --> 00:09:47.119
We can verify this by printing out

174
00:09:47.119 --> 00:09:50.122
the sources.

175
00:09:50.856 --> 00:09:53.526
Lastly, we can ask the question
what is the summary of the paper

176
00:09:53.526 --> 00:09:56.696
to show that the LLM can still pick
the summary tool while necessary.

177
00:10:02.702 --> 00:10:05.571
And we see that it gives back
the right response.

178
00:10:05.571 --> 00:10:06.739
So that's it for lesson two.

179
00:10:06.739 --> 00:10:09.742
And in the next lesson we'll show you
how to build a for agent over a document.

